The '''Silky Sifaka''' or '''Silky Simpona''' ('''''Propithecus candidus''''') is a large [[lemur]] characterized by long, silky white fur and has a restricted range in northeastern [[Madagascar]]. Known locally as the ''simpona'' or ''simpony'', it is one of the rarest mammals on earth, and is listed by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) as one of the world's 25 most critically endangered [[primate]]s.  The Silky Sifaka is one of nine [[sifaka]] species ([[genus]] ''Propithecus''), and one of four former subspecies of [[Diademed Sifaka]] (''P. diadema''). A study in 2004 compared external proportions and genetics, supporting full species status, which was generally adopted over the next few years.

The Silky Sifaka has a variable social structure, and lives in groups of two to nine individuals.  It spends most of its day feeding and resting, though it also devotes a considerable amount of the day to social behaviors, such as playing and grooming, as well as traveling.  Females take priority over males during feeding.  The diet consists primarily of leaves and seeds and is highly varied, consisting of many plant species.  It is a [[seasonal breeder]] and only mates one day a year.  Parental care is shared among adults in the group, as it is with other sifaka species.  The Silky Sifaka has a moderately-sized vocal repertoire consisting of seven calls.  Like all lemurs, it relies strongly on [[Olfaction|scent]] for communication, often scent-marking trees near the center of its range, as opposed to the territory borders.  Males will scent-mark over the top of scent-marks made by other group members, particularly females.  Males also gouge trees with their [[toothcomb]] (a special arrangement of the bottom, front teeth) prior to scent-marking.

The species is only found within a few protected areas in the rainforests of northeastern Madagascar, with the majority of the remaining population in [[Marojejy National Park]] and [[Anjanaharibe-Sud Reserve|Anjanaharibe-Sud Special Reserve]].  A few groups have also been found in the [[Makira Natural Park|Makira Forest Protected Area]], the Betaolana Corridor, and some unprotected forest fragments. The Silky Sifaka is hunted throughout its range as there is no local taboo (''fady'') against eating this species.  Habitat disturbance, such as [[Slash and burn|slash-and-burn agriculture]] (''tavy''), [[Illegal logging in Madagascar|illegal logging of precious woods]] (particularly, [[rosewood]]) and fuel-wood, also occurs within the protected areas where it is found.

==Etymology==
The name "sifaka" is a reference to a common general alarm vocalization given by western dry forest sifakas in which they emit an explosive, hiss-like "shee-faak" call several times in succession.{{r|LoM2_pp341-344}} On the east coast, local residents refer to the larger bodied [[Diademed Sifaka]] as the ''simpona'' or ''simpony'', a name which resembles its sneeze-like "Zzuss!" vocalizations which differs in acoustic structure by gender and individual.{{r|LoM2_pp341-344|1988Simons|Simpona.org}}  The calls are emitted in a variety of stressful circumstances such as presence of humans, falling trees, terrestrial predators, and after receiving aggression.{{r|Simpona.org|2006Patel}} The species name, ''candidus'' is Latin for "white",{{r|1960Borror_p21}} while the species name of the [[Synonym (taxonomy)|taxonomic synonym]], "''sericeus''" is Greek for "silk".{{r|1960Borror_p91}}  

==Taxonomy==
The Silky Sifaka or Silky Simpona was tentatively described in 1871 by French naturalist [[Alfred Grandidier]] in a letter to French zoologist [[Alphonse Milne-Edwards]].  This description was based his on observations north of the [[Bay of Antongil]] in the last few months of 1870.  He then named the species ''Propithecus candidus'' due to its white color, which he likened to that of the [[Verreaux's Sifaka]] (''Propithecus verreauxi''), but without the dark fur on its head or the ash-colored spot on the back. {{r|1871Grandidier}}  The first specimen was obtained in 1872 and provided by "Monsieur Guinet", a farmer from [[Sambava]].  The specimen allowed both Grandidier and Milne-Edwards to formally describe the species based on its skin, [[Fur|coat]], and skull.  This time, they named it ''P. sericeus.''{{r|1872Milne-Edwards}} Upon further review in 1875, Grandidier demoted the Silky Sifaka to a variety or "race" of the [[Diademed Sifaka]] (''P.&nbsp;diadema'').{{r|1875Grandidier}} By the time German zoologist [[Ernst Schwarz]] standardized [[Lemur evolutionary history#Taxonomic and phylogenetic classification|lemur taxonomy]] in 1931, ''P.&nbsp;sericeus'' had become a taxonomic synonym for the species, with the original name, ''Propithecus candidus'', taking priority.{{r|1931Schwarz}}

[[File:Pd candidus AGrandidier.jpg|thumb|left|Color print of the Silky Sifaka from Alfred Grandidier's ''L'Histoire politique, physique et naturelle de Madagascar''. (1892)]]
Schwarz placed all sifakas into two species, the larger [[Diademed Sifaka]] (''P. diadema'') from the [[Madagascar lowland forests|eastern rainforests]] and the smaller [[Verreaux's Sifaka]] (''P.&nbsp;verreauxi'') from the [[Madagascar dry deciduous forests|dry forests]] and [[Madagascar spiny thickets|spiny forests]] of the west and south.  At the time, both species were comprised of four [[subspecies]], and the Silky Sifaka was listed as ''P.&nbsp;diadema&nbsp;candidus'', a subspecies of the Diademed Sifaka.{{r|1931Schwarz|2007Groves}}  In his 1982 book ''[[Primates of Madagascar (book)|Primates of Madagascar]]'', anthropologist [[Ian Tattersall]] upheld this classification.{{r|2007Tattersall}}  When anthropologist [[Colin Groves]] reviewed the taxonomy in his book ''[[Primate Taxonomy (book)|Primate Taxonomy]]'' in 2001, he also upheld the subspecies status of the Silky Sifaka because variations in fur coloration between the available specimens suggested converging similarities with the Diademed Sifaka's coloration.{{r|2007Groves|2001Groves}}  Groves later noted that the coloration of the two species did not overlap, suggesting that the populations were distinct.{{r|2007Groves}}

In 2004, [[Mireya Mayor|Mayor]] ''et al''. showed that despite having a similar [[karyotype]] (the number and appearance of [[chromosome]]s) of 42&nbsp;chromosomes (2n=42), the Silky Sifaka was distinct from the Diademed Sifaka.  This was shown through genetic tests ([[D-loop]] sequencing) and by comparing external proportions.  For example, the Silky Sifaka is larger-bodied than the Diademed Sifaka and has a shorter tail.{{r|2007Groves|2004Mayor}}  Their analysis indicated a closer relationship with [[Perrier's Sifaka]] (''Propithecus perrieri'').{{r|2004Mayor}}  [[Russell Mittermeier]] ''et al''. followed by adopting the full species status of the Silky Sifaka for the 2nd edition of ''[[Lemurs of Madagascar (book)|Lemurs of Madagascar]]'' in 2006.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387}}  Although Groves maintained the Silky Sifaka as a subspecies in the 3rd edition of ''[[Mammal Species of the World]]'' in 2005,{{r|MSW3}} he recognized it as a distinct species in 2007 by acknowledging the work of Mayor ''et al''. and also noting the additional distinction that the Silky Sifaka has relatively long [[Molar (tooth)|molar teeth]] compared to the length of its toothrow.{{r|2007Groves}}  Despite the promotion to full species status, the Silky Sifaka is still considered to be a member of the ''P.&nbsp;diadema'' group, a group of four closely related, large-bodied, eastern rainforest sifakas.  The other three members of this group are the Diademed Sifaka, Perrier's Sifaka,  and [[Milne-Edwards' Sifaka]] (''Propithecus edwardsi'').{{r|LoM2_pp341-344|2007Groves}}  The species status of the Silky Sifaka, as well as other sifakas, does not have universal support:{{r|LoM2_pp341-344}}  in 2007, Tattersall argued against species distinctions within ''Propithecus'', claiming the decisions were made prematurely.{{r|2007Tattersall}}

In 1974, Tattersall spotted what he thought was a color variant of the Silky Sifaka north of [[Vohemar]] in northeast Madagascar.  Describing it as such eight years later in ''The Primates of Madagascar'', he not only cited its mostly white fur, but also uncharacteristic traits such as a patch of orange on its crown and tufted ears.  It was not observed again until 1986, when a team led by paleoanthropologist [[Elwyn Simons]] captured specimens for [[captive breeding]] and identified it as a new species, named as the [[Golden-crowned Sifaka]] (''Propithecus tattersalli'') in 1988.{{r|1988Simons|1990Harcourt}}

==Geographic range and habitat==
The Silky Sifaka is confined to a small region of northeastern Madagascar within a strip of humid forest stretching from [[Maroantsetra]] in the south to the [[Andapa Basin]] and the [[Marojejy Massif]] in the north. [[Marojejy National Park]] represents the northern limit of its current distribution,{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2009Patel}} although historical sifaka range maps created by Grandidier and Milne-Edwards in the late 19th century show the Silky Sifaka as far north as the [[Bemarivo River]], north of [[Sambava]].{{r|1875Grandidier|1982Tattersall|2006Wilm<U+00E9>}}  The [[Androranga River]] may represent the northwestern range limit within the [[Tsaratanana Corridor]].{{r|2009Patel}} The southern limit of its range appears to be the [[Antainambalana River]], within the [[Makira Conservation Site]].{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2009Patel|2007Rasolofoson}} It is not known if the Silky Sifaka has ever ranged as far south as the [[Masoala Peninsula]].{{r|1982Tattersall|1990Harcourt}} As of 2009, new observations of a few groups of the Silky Sifaka in unprotected forest fragments adjacent to northeastern Makira ([[Antohaka Lava]] and [[Maherivaratra]]) may slightly enlarge the known geographic range of this species.{{r|2009Patel}}  The presence of the Silky Sifaka has been documented within Marojejy National Park,{{r|2009Patel|1955Humbert|1975Guillaumet|1995Duckworth|2000Sterling}} [[Anjanaharibe-Sud Reserve|Anjanaharibe-Sud Special Reserve]],{{r|2009Patel|1998Schmid}} the [[Makira Natural Park|Makira Forest Protected Area]],{{r|2009Patel|2007Rasolofoson|2008Patel}} the [[Betaolana Corridor]],{{r|2009Patel|2003Goodman}} and the Tsaratanana Corridor.  In 2008, 16&nbsp;groups were discovered in western Marojejy near Antsahaberoaka.{{r|2009Patel}}

The Silky Sifaka tends to be found at higher elevations than any of the other sifaka species and also occupies the greatest range of elevations for the group.{{r|2009Patel}} In Marojejy National Park and Anjanaharibe-Sud Special Reserve, where most of the remaining groups exist, it is not found below {{convert|700|m|ft|abbr=on}} of elevation and not above {{convert|1875|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{r|2009Patel|2008Patel|2006Irwin}}  However, at its southernmost location in Makira (Andaparaty), several groups inhabit forest fragments at an unusually low elevation of {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{r|2009Patel}}  The Silky Sifaka inhabits three types of elevation-specific habitats: primary [[Cloud forest|montane rainforest]], [[Sclerophyll|sclerophyllous forest]], and the most elevated portions of low [[Madagascar ericoid thickets|ericoid bush]].{{r|2009Patel}} It is unknown how sensitive the Silky Sifaka is to disturbance or whether it avoids habitat edges ("edge-intolerant") or is more edge-tolerant like the Diademed Sifaka.  Like other rainforest sifaka species, it seldom crosses non-forested regions between forest fragments.{{r|2008Patel}}

In the Anjanaharibe-Sud Special Reserve, the Silky Sifaka is [[Sympatric speciation|sympatric]] (shares the same geographic range) with the [[White-fronted Brown Lemur]] (''Eulemur albifrons'') and an all-black population of [[Indri]] (''Indri indri'').  In Marojejy National Park, it is sympatric with the White-fronted Brown Lemur.{{r|LoM2_pp431-455}} In 2008, it was suggested that the Silky Sifaka may be sympatric with the [[Red Ruffed Lemur]] (''Varecia rubra'') near Maherivaratra and Andaparaty.{{r|2009Patel|2008Patel}}

==Physical description==
{{Double image stack|right|Chest Patch Makira.jpg|Silky Sifaka Pink Face Closeup.JPG|225|Male Silky Sifakas have a prominent chest patch due to scent marking (top), and all individuals exhibit variation in skin pigmentation (bottom).|||}}

The Silky Sifaka is one of the larger sifaka species, with a head-body length of {{convert|48|<U+2013>|54|cm|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}, a tail length of {{convert|45|<U+2013>|51|cm|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}, a total length of {{convert|93|<U+2013>|105|cm|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}, and a weight of {{convert|5|<U+2013>|6.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2009Patel|2005Lehman|2007Garbutt_187-189}} As its common English name suggests, its long, white [[fur]] has a silky texture. Not all individuals are completely white: some have silver-gray or black tints on the crown, back, and limbs. The base of the tail ("pygal region") can be yellow.  The ears and face are hairless, and the skin may be a mix of pink and black, completely black, or completely pink. The tips of the ears protrude slightly above the fur on the rest of the head.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2009Patel}}  Its eyes have a deep orange-red coloration.{{r|2007Garbutt_187-189}} Its appearance is distinctive, and since no other sifakas share its range, it is not easily confused with other lemur species.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2009Patel}}

While it is difficult to distinguish adult males and females in other eastern rainforest sifakas, such as the Perrier's Sifaka and Milne-Edwards' Sifaka, gender in the Silky Sifaka is much easier to discern due to differences in fur coloration of the upper chest. Females have white fur, while males have a large brown patch of fur that results from [[Territory (animal)|scent marking]] with a gland on the chest and throat (the sternal gular gland).  During mating season, the size of the "chest patch" increases to cover both the chest and abdomen as a result of increased scent marking.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2009Patel}}

==Behavior==
Until the 21st century, brief observations and lemur surveys had merely documented the presence of the Silky Sifaka in special reserves and national parks. More recently, a 14-month study and two short-term studies in Marojejy National Park have revealed previously unknown details about its behavioral biology, communication, and feeding ecology.{{r|2009Patel|LoM1_pp249-250}}  The Silky Sifaka has a variable social structure and is known to live in [[Pair bond|male-female pairs]], [[one-male group]]s, and [[Multi-male group|multi-male/multi-female groups]]. Group sizes range from two to nine individuals, while the [[home range]]s are estimated to range from {{convert|34|to|47|ha|sqmi|abbr=on}}, varying in size by location.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2009Patel|2008Patel|2006bPatel}}

[[File:Silky sifaka Allocare.JPG|thumb|left|Nonmaternal infant care often occurs in silky sifakas. A mother carrying more than her own infant is rare.]]
According to some studies, the Silky Sifaka spends most of its day resting and feeding (approximately 44.4% and 25% respectively).  It also devotes approximately 16.8% of the day to social behavior, such as [[personal grooming]], [[social grooming]] (allogrooming), and play.  The rest of the day is spent traveling and sleeping.{{r|2009Patel}}  Other sources report that the species divides half of the day between traveling and foraging, while the rest is spent resting.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387}} Daily foraging usually starts at dawn unless delayed by rain.  Group movement is usually led by females, and groups usually travel {{convert|700|m|ft|abbr=on}} per day, and may climb {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} along vertical slopes.{{r|2007Garbutt_187-189}} Although the species spends its time in the trees, terrestrial play is not uncommon, even among adults,{{r|2006bPatel}} with play sessions lasting 30&nbsp;minutes or more.{{r|2007Garbutt_187-189}} Like other sifakas, it uses a type of [[arboreal locomotion]] known as [[vertical clinging and leaping]].{{r|2007Garbutt_187-189}} [[Dominance hierarchy|Dominance hierarchies]] have not been documented among female sifakas, including the Silky Sifaka, although seasonal hierarchies are known to occur.{{r|2007aPatel}} [[Aggression]], which is generally infrequent, occurs primarily during feeding, where females take priority over males,{{r|2006bPatel}} although submissive signals are not always obvious.{{r|2007Garbutt_187-189}}

The Silky Sifaka's diet is similar to that of other eastern rainforest sifakas, consisting primarily of leafs ([[Folivore|folivory]]) and seeds ([[seed predation]]).  It is highly varied and includes many plant species.{{r|2009Patel}}  A 2-month study from the mid-2000s showed that the Silky Sifaka can feed on as many as 76&nbsp;species of plant from 42&nbsp;[[Family (biology)|families]].  Its favorites included primarily tree species, but also some [[liana]]s.  The most prominent plant families in the diet were [[Moraceae]] (20.30%), [[Fabaceae]] (12.87%), [[Myrtaceae]] (12.65%), [[Clusiaceae]] (10.13%) and [[Apocynaceae]] (9.49%).  In the study, feeding upon these four plant families took up as much as 37.06% of the total feeding time for the Silky Sifaka: 16.09% on the fruit of ''[[Pachytrophe dimepate]]'', 8.43% on the seeds of ''[[Senna (genus)|Senna]]'' sp., 6.52% on the young leaves of ''[[Plectaneia thouarsii]]'', and 6.02% on the fruit of ''[[Eugenia]]'' sp.  In sum, folivory accounted for 52% of the feeding time, while [[Frugivore|frugivory]] (fruit-eating) accounted for 34%, and seed predation made up 11%. The consumption of flowers, as well as soil ([[geophagy]]), was rarely observed in this study.{{r|2009Patel|2008Queslin}}  Prior to this, preliminary studies had reported that folivory account for 75% of the diet, while fruits and 15% was seed predation, 7% was flower consumption, and bark and soil made up the remainder.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387}}

Like all other lemurs, the Silky Sifaka is a [[seasonal breeder]], and it is thought that it [[Mating|mates]] only one day a year sometime during December or January. Infants are born six months later in June or July. Females typically give birth to a single infant once every two years, although births in consecutive years have been observed. Infants initially cling to the fur of their mother's chest for nearly four weeks and then switch to riding on her back.  As with other eastern rainforest sifakas, the infants of this species develop rapidly.  This may be due to assistance in the care of infants by all group members (known as [[alloparental care]])<U+2014>a trait typical among all sifakas.  Non-maternal care usually takes the form of allogrooming, but also playing, occasional carrying, and in rare cases, nursing.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2009Patel|2007aPatel|2003Patel}}  The dispersal of offspring is thought to be similar to that of other  eastern rainforest sifakas, with both males and females transferring out of the group at [[sexual maturity]]. However, dispersal has only been observed once with a young adult male, who left its natal group and proceeded to oust an older male from a group in which he had been a member for seven years.  Female dispersal and group transfer has not yet been observed.{{r|2009Patel}}

