The only documented predator of the Silky Sifaka, other than humans, is the [[Fossa (animal)|Fossa]], a [[Feliformia|cat-like carnivore]] found only on Madagascar.{{r|2005Patel}}  Although no aerial predators are known, the Silky Sifaka often watch the sky and emit loud "aerial disturbance" roars at the sight of the large [[Madagascar buzzard]] (''Buteo brachypterus'') and other small birds.{{r|2009Patel}}  Another more general alarm call is the loud, sneeze-like ''zzuss'' [[Animal communication|vocalization]], which are emitted in response to terrestrial disturbances, calls from lost group members, and aggression by other group members.  Acoustic analyses of the ''zzuss'' vocalization have shown that the call's [[Acoustics|acoustic]] structure differs between individuals and by gender.{{r|Simpona.org|2006Patel|2009Patel|2005aPatel|2003aPatel}}

Adult eastern sifakas have a moderately sized vocal repertoire of about seven call types.{{r|2005bPatel}} It is uncertain if their vocalizations have specific or varied contexts, and as with other primates, arousal level may play a role in the acoustic structure of its calls.{{r|2008Owren}} Despite the limited size of the Silky Sifaka's vocal repertoire, it does exhibit high call rates of seven calls per hour, on average. Even infants are known to have several specialized vocalizations.{{r|2008Gron}} The most frequently emitted Silky Sifaka vocalizations are low amplitude, low frequency, tonal ''hum'' and ''mum'' vocalizations. These contact calls are used in a variety of circumstances including group movement, affiliation, foraging, and while resting.{{r|Simpona.org}}

The Silky Sifaka uses well-developed [[Olfaction|olfactory]] (smell-based) communication, as with all other [[prosimian]] ("pre-monkey") primates.  Like other eastern rainforest sifakas, it has several specialized glands for [[Territory (animal)|scent-marking]], including a [[sebaceous gland]] on the chest, found only in males, and mixed [[Apocrine sweat gland|apocrine]]-sebaceous glands on the [[Sex organ|genitals]] in both sexes.{{r|2009Patel|1979Schilling}} Unlike the [[true lemur]]s of the genus ''Eulemur'', the Silky Sifaka does not directly scent-mark its [[wikt:conspecific|conspecifics]] ([[allomark]]ing), although it does scent-mark its territory.  Both sexes will often urinate while scent-marking.  Males and females scent-mark in different ways: females rub their genital glands in an up-and-down motion against trees, while males may use their chest gland, genital glands, or a combination of both.{{r|2009Patel}} Males will also use their specialized prosimian [[toothcomb]] to gouge trees before scent-marking with their chest<U+2014>a behavior that leaves long-lasting visible marks.  The gouging it thought to serve a role in communication and has no dietary component, since males do not eat the bark or tree gum.{{r|2009Patel|2008aPatel}}

Males scent-mark more frequently than females, as much as two or three times as often.  Males also respond to female scent-marking by overmarking with their own scent glands, usually by combining chest and genital marking.  They will also overmark other males, although less quickly and less often.  In a one-year study, males responded to 71% of the marks made by females within an average of 61&nbsp;seconds while only 17% of male marks received a response from other group members.{{r|2009Patel|2006aPatel|2007Andrianandrasana}}  Because males overmark frequently, this results in "totem-tree marking", where certain trees become covered by male scent and gouge marks.  However, no observations of widespread home range border scent-marking have been reported.{{r|2009Patel|2008aPatel|2006aPatel|2006Ritchie}} Scent-marks are usually left on trees in the core area of the home range, as opposed to the territorial boundaries.{{r|LoM2_pp383-387|2007Garbutt_187-189}}

